3 EmptyDrops

3.1 Test the effect of different values of \(T\) on the p-value distribution

In EmptyDrops(), first a set \(G\) of barcodes \(b\) is defined such that for \(b \in G\), \(t_{b} \le T\). Where \(t_{b}\) is the total number of UMIs in barcode b, and \(T\) is a threshold value. \(G\) represents the set of empty barcodes that contain UMIs less than or equal to a set threshold. The exact value of \(T\) does not matter, as long as (i) it is small enough that droplets containing genuine cells are not included in \(G\) and (ii) large enough that there is a sufficient number of reads to create the ambient profile. A way of making sure that we are not using an inappropriate value of \(T\) is to make sure that the distribution of p values is uniform for barcodes with \(t_{b} < T\). This is what Lun et al did too in their paper.

I ran emptyDrops with \(T = {25, 50, 100, 200, 400}\) parameters and plotted the p value distribution for barcodes with \(0 < t_{b} \le T\).

### test different values of T
limits <- c(25, 50, 100, 200, 400, 800)

for(i in samples){
  for(j in limits){
    set.seed(100)
    all.out <- emptyDrops(counts(get(i)), lower = j, test.ambient = TRUE)
    
    # create histogram
    plt.dat <- as.data.frame(all.out[all.out$Total <= j & all.out$Total > 0, ])
    
    assign(paste0('hist.', i, '.', j),
           ggplot(data = plt.dat, aes(x = PValue)) +
             geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.025, boundary= 0.5, 
                            fill = 'grey80', 
                            color = 'black', 
                            size = 0.25) +
             labs(title = paste0(i, ", T = ", j)) +
             theme_minimal() +
             theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
                   panel.grid.major = element_line(size = 0.25))
    )
    
    # save histogram
    ggsave(get(paste0('hist.', i, '.', j)), 
           filename = paste0('emptydrops_hist-pval_', i, '_', j, '.pdf'), 
           path = '../results/03_emptydrops/', 
           width = 4, height = 3, units = 'in')
  }
}

For all samples, at all values of \(T\), there is a strange abundance of high p values. Those are always hard to interpret. David Robinson has a good explanation of how to interpret p value distributions on his blog Variance Explained. This could happen if you are running a one-tailed test, or if your p values have already been corrected for multiple testing (not the case here, I think). But there are also pathological cases in which this can happen: when your data dont meet certain assumptions of your tests, e.g.normality or independence. Not sure what exactly is happening here (another reason to write to Aaron Lun to clarify this).

If we ignore that end of the distribution for a minute and focus on the p values close to 0, there is a pattern. For almost all amphioxus samples, the distribution at this end is quite flat for \(T = 25\) and for \(T = 50\), but for values of \(T > 50\), you start seeing an uptick of low p values.

This suggests that at \(T > 50\), and especially at \(T >= 200\), we include real cells in the ambient profile. I will proceed with \(T = 50\) and \(T = 100\) for running emptyDrops on all these samples.

3.2.1 Barcode ranks, knee, and inflection point

### barcode ranks, knee, and inflection point =================================
# calculate barcode ranks
bcrank.phar <- barcodeRanks(counts(phar))

bcrank.hgut <- barcodeRanks(counts(hgut))

# get unique ranks for plotting speed

# plot umi ~ bcrank
for (i in samples){
  # assign variables
  infl <- metadata(get(paste0('bcrank.', i)))$inflection
  knee <- metadata(get(paste0('bcrank.', i)))$knee
  dat <- as.data.frame(get(paste0("bcrank.", i, ".u")))
  
  # assing plot to brcplt.i object
  assign(paste0('bcrplt.', i), 
         ggplot(data = dat, aes(x = rank, y = total)) +
           geom_point(shape = 21, alpha = 0.75) +
           scale_x_log10() +
           scale_y_log10() +
           geom_hline(yintercept = infl, color = "red", lty = 2) +
           geom_hline(yintercept = knee, color = "blue", lty = 2) +
           annotate(geom = "text", x = max(dat$rank) * 0.75, y = infl, 
                    label = paste0("inflection: ", infl), 
                    vjust = -0.5, hjust = 1) +
           annotate(geom = "text", x = max(dat$rank) * 0.75, y = knee, 
                    label = paste0("knee: ", knee), 
                    vjust = -0.5, hjust = 1) +
           labs(title = i) +
           xlab("Barcode rank") +
           ylab("Total UMI count") +
           theme_bw() +
           theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
                 panel.grid.major = element_line(size = 0.25))
  )
  
  # save
  ggsave(get(paste0('bcrplt.', i)), 
         filename = paste0('emptydrops_bcrank_', i, '.pdf'),

3.2.2 Run emptyDrops with \(T = 100\) and \(T = 200\)

# run emptydrops
for(i in samples){
  for(j in c(100, 200)){
    set.seed(100)
    assign(
      paste0('e.out.', i, '.', j),
      emptyDrops(counts(get(i)), lower = j)
    )
  }
}

3.2.3 Diagnostic plots

3.2.3.1 -logProb ~ UMI plots

# make -logProb ~ UMI count plots for for T values, and FDR 0.01 and 0.001
# Note: Using `aes(color = FDR <= k)` results in FALSE and TRUE values, and alphabetically FALSE points are plotted first and TRUE points are plotted on top. This makes the FALSE points at the bottom left not be visible at all. To change plotting order, plot them manually, with manual color assignment, and add legend manually. Instructions from here: https://aosmith.rbind.io/2018/07/19/manual-legends-ggplot2/
for(i in samples){
  for(j in c(100, 200)){
    dat <- as.data.frame(get(paste0("e.out.", i, ".", j)))
    dat <- dat[!is.na(dat$FDR), ]
    
    for(k in c(0.01, 0.001)){
      assign(paste0("logPplot.", i, ".", j, ".", k),
             ggplot(data = dat, aes(x = Total/1000, y = -LogProb/1000)) +
               geom_point(data = dat[dat$FDR <= k, ],
                          aes(fill = "#377EB8"), 
                          alpha = 0.5, shape = 21, color = "white", 
                          stroke = 0.25, size = 2) +
               geom_point(data = dat[dat$FDR > k, ],
                          aes(fill = "#E41A1C"), 
                          alpha = 0.5, shape = 21, color = "white", 
                          stroke = 0.25, size = 2) +
               scale_fill_identity(name = "FDR <= threshold",
                                   breaks = c("#377EB8", "#E41A1C"),
                                   labels = c("TRUE", "FALSE"),
                                   guide = "legend") +
               labs(subtitle = paste0(i,", T = ", j, ", FDR ", k)) +
               xlab("UMI (x 1000)") +
               ylab("-LogProb (x 1000)") +
               theme_minimal()
      )
    }
  }
}

3.2.3.2 Barcode rank plots with cell calling output

Barcode rank plots with points coloured by \(FDR \le 0.01\).

# plots
for(i in samples){
  # barcode ranks (unique for plotting speed)
  bcr <- as.data.frame(get(paste0("bcrank.", i))) %>% unique()
  
  # emptydrops output
  ed <- get(paste0("e.out.", i, ".200"))
  
  # add e.out FDR values to bcrank table
  bcr$FDR <- ed$FDR[match(x = rownames(bcr), table = rownames(ed))]
  
  # plot
  assign(
    paste0("bcr.fdr.plt.", i),
    ggplot(data = bcr, aes(x = rank, y = total)) +
      geom_point(aes(color = FDR <= 0.01), alpha = 0.65) +
      scale_x_log10() +
      scale_y_log10() +
      labs(title = paste0(i, ", T = 200")) +
      xlab("Barcode rank") +
      ylab("Total UMI count") +
      theme_minimal()
  )
  
  # save
  ggsave(get(paste0('bcr.fdr.plt.', i)), 
         filename = paste0('emptydrops_bcrankFDRplot_', i, '.pdf'), 
         path = here(basedir, "results", "03_emptydrops"), 
         width = 5.5, height = 3.5, units = 'in')
}
